<HEADLINE>
<P>
LORD HAROLD CACCIA; BRITISH DIPLOMAT TO WASHINGTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lord Harold Caccia, 84, a former British ambassador to Washington. Caccia, 
described by contemporaries as one of the most skilled and effective British 
diplomats of his generation, was assigned to Washington from 1956 to 1961 to 
restore confidence after the crisis over the short-lived invasion of the Suez 
Canal region. 
</P>
<P>
Britain was severely criticized over the Anglo-French-Israeli invasion that 
same year, a response to Egypt's nationalization of the strategic waterway. 
Upon his retirement in 1965, he was made Baron Caccia and became director to a 
number of companies. He also became provost of Eton College. The Caccia family 
originated in Tuscany -- it is mentioned in Canto 29 of Dante's Purgatory -- 
and settled in England in the early 19th Century. The British Foreign Office 
said over the weekend that Caccia died Oct. 31 in Builth Wells, Wales, but did 
not give the cause of death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
