<HEADLINE>
<P>
1 WORKER KILLED, 2 HURT IN BLAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One worker was killed and two were injured Sunday when a turbine engine 
exploded at a Kearny Mesa industrial plant, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred about 6:40 p.m. in a work yard at Solar Turbines Inc. on 
Ruffin Road when a compressor undergoing an air pressure test exploded, company 
spokesman Larry Sera said. 
</P>
<P>
The two injured men, who were not identified late Sunday, were taken to Sharp 
Memorial Hospital. One man suffered burns to his shoulder; the other suffered a 
broken wrist and second- and third-degree burns. 
</P>
<P>
"A cap came off the compressor," Sera said. "I don't know if the cap hit the 
men or the blast of air got them." 
</P>
<P>
Remaining employees were sent home after the accident, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The compressor is normally used to compress natural gas but was undergoing a 
routine test at the time of the explosion, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Solar Turbines manufactures gas turbine engines and places them in machines 
that compress gas, generate electricity or pump liquids, Sera said. 
</P>
<P>
The California Occupational Safety and Health Administration will look into the 
accident today, authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
