<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
DISCOVERING THE LETHAL SIDE OF HERBS; 
</P>
<P>
PLANTS: COMFREY IS FOUND TO BE PARTICULARLY DAMAGING TO THE LIVER. MANY OTHER 
POTENTIALLY TOXIC HERBAL PRODUCTS ARE BEING SOLD, EXPERTS FEAR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES DOWNEY, Charles Downey is a syndicated journalist and magazine 
writer in Fawnskin, Calif. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 49-year-old woman had developed a rare liver ailment with symptoms seen 
only in chemotherapy patients, end-stage cirrhosis of the liver and a rare type 
of liver poisoning caused by a substance known as pyrrolizidine alkaloids. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Paul M. Ridker, a cardiology fellow at Brigham and Women's Hospital at 
Harvard Medical School, knew the woman did not drink and had never undergone 
chemotherapy. He also knew there had never been a case of pyrrolizidine 
poisoning reported in North America. But nothing else explained the woman's 
symptoms. 
</P>
<P>
"We eventually found the woman had been drinking large amounts of comfrey tea 
and taking comfrey pepsin tablets daily for six months," Ridker says. "We later 
analyzed the tea and tablets in the lab and found the preparations contained 
large amounts of pyrrolizidine alkaloids, which caused her liver disease. 
</P>
<P>
"Harvard is a major teaching hospital but it took us four years to link the 
comfrey with the liver disease. My point is, I think the herb problem is much 
larger than physicians realize and that many other such cases are going 
unreported." 
</P>
<P>
Ridker and others now recommend that people avoid food products containing 
comfrey, but their concern is not limited to comfrey. Experts are becoming 
increasingly wary of other herbs, herbal teas and other herbal preparations. 
They are concerned that many potentially toxic herbs may be sold in health food 
stores, drugstores and even supermarkets. 
</P>
<P>
Sales of herbal products are large -- anywhere from half a billion to a billion 
dollars yearly, according to the the Herb Research Foundation. The sales are 
spurred by claims that comfrey, for instance, is good for wound healing and 
aiding digestion. Other herbs, like aloe, are used in hopes they will soothe 
burns and wounds or remove excess gasses from the gastrointestinal tract. 
</P>
<P>
Says William Jarvis, professor of preventive medicine at Loma Linda University 
and president of the National Council Against Health Fraud Inc.: "Herbs can 
actually be very potent medications. However, mother nature doesn't supply a 
standard dose. A herb can be stronger, or weaker, depending on the part of the 
plant consumed, the time of the year it was harvested, how long it has been 
stored and even if it was a dry year when picked." 
</P>
<P>
Although the majority of herb products are probably safe, experts say at least 
26 commonly available herbs contain toxic compounds which have caused disease 
in the gastrointestinal, cardiac and nervous systems. Other herbal-caused 
health concerns have ranged from liver failure to skin inflammation to abortion 
to lowered blood pressure to death. 
</P>
<P>
After comfrey, the most dangerous herbs, say Ridker and other experts, are 
buckthorn, pokeroot and teas with pure licorice, all of which may contribute to 
high blood pressure. Teas made with tonka beans, woodruff or elilot, herbs that 
contain organic coumarins, can suppress coagulation. Even every grandmother's 
favorite, sassafras, can be dangerous to the liver because of its high content 
of safrole. 
</P>
<P>
When Ridker looked up articles about the unusual poisoning printed in 
scientific journals, he became even more concerned. He discovered that a woman 
in England had died because she consumed a lot of comfrey tea. In the early 
1970s, a weed containing pyrrolizidine alkaloids fell into some wheat being 
harvested in Afghanistan. When the farmers and their families consumed bread 
made from the contaminated wheat, 25% of the 7,200 villagers developed the 
liver ailment within two years. 
</P>
<P>
Other outbreaks of such poisoning have occurred in Jamaica, Africa and India 
after people consumed comfrey or other plants containing the liver-damaging 
substance. In one case in Switzerland, a pregnant woman drank a tea containing 
pyrrolizidine alkaloids and gave birth to a baby with a damaged liver. 
</P>
<P>
Groundsel and gordolobo, two other widely available herbs, also contain 
pyrrolizidine alkaloids. 
</P>
<P>
New Zealand, Japan and Canada have banned most comfrey and comfrey products. 
The U.S. Food and Drug Administration is investigating comfrey products and 
considering a ban. 
</P>
<P>
Experts say many consumers regard herbs and other plant products as harmless 
because they grow naturally in our good earth. However, cocaine, opium, tobacco 
and marijuana, which are far from harmless, can all be considered herbs. 
</P>
<P>
R. Frank Chandler, professor of pharmacy and director of the College of 
Pharmacy at Dalhousie University in Halifax, Canada, analyzed 65 popular herbs 
such as pokeberry, chamomile, feverfew and cayenne. Chandler then summarized 
the herbs' main ingredients, their major uses, safety and side effects. (See 
chart.) 
</P>
<P>
"The safety of herbs depends on the herb under consideration and how it's 
prepared," says Chandler. "Just because a herb has been used for several 
thousand years for a particular purpose, there's no guarantee it's safe or 
effective. Moreover, there are cases of herbs interacting with prescription 
medications." 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, because the Federal Drug Administration has classified herbs as food 
products -- and not drugs -- manufacturers are not required to prove that herbs 
are safe or effective. Thus, willy-nilly herbal use can be risky. 
</P>
<P>
However, the herbal picture is not all as dark as death. 
</P>
<P>
"Except for comfrey, I'm not concerned about herbs or herbal teas consumed in 
reasonable, ordinary amounts," says Norman Fransworth, a professor in the 
College of Pharmacy at the University of Illinois at Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
"True herbalism includes scientific testing, honest reporting of the results 
and safe use of effective herbs by informed practitioners," says Varro E. 
Tyler, vice president for academic affairs and professor of pharmacognosy at 
Purdue. Pharmacognosy is the study of drugs derived from natural products. 
</P>
<P>
"Herb use can be a Dr. Jekyll-and-Mr. Hyde situation," says Tyler, who is also 
the author of "The New Honest Herbal" (J. B. Lippincott Co.) He says " 
'Paraherbalism,' a pseudoscience about herb use, is usually characterized by 
popular myths." He lists them as: 
</P>
<P>
* Herbs are "natural" and do no harm. 
</P>
<P>
* Whole herbs are more effective than their isolated active constituents. 
</P>
<P>
* "Natural" and "organic" herbs are superior to synthetic drugs. 
</P>
<P>
* Astrological influences may be significant. (Some practitioners prescribe 
herbs according to astrological signs.) 
</P>
<P>
* Tests in animals are not applicable to human beings. 
</P>
<P>
The American Botanical Council, an herbal educational group in Austin, Tex., is 
promoting a new regulatory classification for herbs, called "traditional 
medicines." 
</P>
<P>
"That category would let us review the safety and efficacy of herbs," says Mark 
Blumenthal, executive director. "Currently, it costs somewhere around $125 
million to get one new drug approved in the United States. And, we do need to 
provide for appropriate labeling of herbs so the proper directions can be 
given. But in the present regulatory climate created by the federal government, 
that's just impossible. Consumers are not getting adequate directions for 
taking herbs although it's clear people really want these products. Eventually, 
we would like to develop an American Botanical Code, which would be a thorough 
and authoritative reference work on herbs." 
</P>
<P>
According to the council, only about 2% of 500 commonly available herbs have 
been subjected to clinical testing. Of the herbs that have been tested, 
feverfew has been used by physicians to treat migraine; gingko leaf extract is 
used for circulatory problems, tinnitus and short-term memory loss; milk 
thistle seed extract is used for liver toxicity conditions, and valerian root 
ingredients became a sedative. About 25% of prescription medications were first 
taken or synthesized from plants, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
Ryan J. Huxtable, professor of pharmacology at the University of Arizona, 
suggests the following guidelines for consuming herbs: 
</P>
<P>
* If ill, see a physician, not an herbalist. 
</P>
<P>
* Do not take herbs if you are pregnant, nursing or trying to get pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
* Do not take a large quantity of one preparation or on a daily basis. 
</P>
<P>
* Use only preparations that list the plants on the package. 
</P>
<P>
* Do not consume anything that contains comfrey. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
POTENTIALLY HARMFUL HERBS 
</P>
<P>
The following are some herbs used for various physical problems 
</P>
<P>
HERB: MAJOR USES: SIDE EFFECTS: COMMENTS: 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Comfrey 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: wound healing, digestion aid 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: harmful to the liver 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: contains high levels of pyrrolizide alkaloids. 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Feverfew 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: migrain prevention fever reduction gas removal from GI tract help 
menstral flow 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: oral ulcers 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: not for use during pregnancy 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Goldenseal 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: digestion aid stop bleeding after childbirth 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: --- 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: dangerous in high doses 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Juniper 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: diuretic, antiseptic flavoring reduce GI gasses 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: kidney irritation dermatitis 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: not to be used during pregnancy or kidney disease 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Poke root 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: laxative, antirheumatic,respiratory tract conditions 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: severe cramping vomiting, weakness low blood pressure spasms 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: should not be consumed 
</P>
<P>
HERB: Sassafras 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR USES: antirheumatic, diuretic 
</P>
<P>
SIDE EFFECTS: toxic to liver, carcinogenic 
</P>
<P>
COMMENTS: listed by FDA as a food adulterant 
</P>
<P>
Source: R. Frank Chandler, Dalhousie University 
</P>
</TEXT>
