<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
A TERRITORIAL ISSUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NATALIE SALAZAR, NATALIE SALAZAR, executive director of the Lomita-based 
Community Reclamation Project, a gang-prevention program, commented on 
competition among social programs for dwindling funds. She told The Times: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Here in Los Angeles there is a lot of jealousy and infighting among people and 
programs who have good ideas but keep them to themselves. It's a territorial 
issue over who is going to get the best publicity in order to get funding. 
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, there was a broader funding base for social programs and more 
federal money. Today, there is a lack of money and funding alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
The bottom line is nobody is an expert (on gangs) because the problem keeps 
changing so rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one of the discouraging things we see now is law enforcement taking 
on the (former) role of community-based programs to divert young men and women 
from gang activity. 
</P>
<P>
I'm glad they are trying to get involved. (But) we need to use the 
community-based prevention programs already out there; otherwise, funding 
sources may continue to dwindle as public agencies attempt to take over their 
role. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
