<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: PEOPLE WATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Myths in the Making: Martial-arts movie star Steven Seagal seems to have 
trouble separating myth from reality. He recently appeared on Arsenio Hall's 
talk show and said that he spent a lot of his youth in Brooklyn, but his 
mother, Pat, told People magazine that he was born in Lansing, Mich., and lived 
outside Detroit before moving to Fullerton, Calif., when he was 5. 
</P>
<P>
Seagal also has portrayed himself as an urban street kid, but his mother says 
he suffered from asthma and was "a puny kid back then." The People story also 
casts doubt on Seagal's claim to have studied in Japan with Morihei Uyeshiba, 
the founder of the aikido form of martial arts, who died in 1969. Sources 
familiar with the CIA also say Seagal's claim to have been a CIA adviser is 
improbable. CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Seagal 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
