<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Canadian Punkers Not Obscene: A Canadian jury has found two records by the punk 
rock group DayGlo Abortions not obscene. The jury ruled Thursday that the 
albums, "Feed Us a Fetus" and "Here Today Guano Tomorrow" -- which are laced 
with four-letter words and describe sex, satanism, bestiality, rape, murder and 
suicide -- are not obscene as charged under Canada's criminal code. Band 
members, with names such as Cretin, Couch Potato and Jesus Bonehead, contend 
that the songs are parodies intended to shock. CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
