<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Memorabilia in Demand: Sales of paintings may be falling, but the market for 
film collectibles remains strong, as indicated by estimated prices for the 
upcoming auction of Hollywood posters of the '20s and '30s at Christie's East 
in New York City. Among the items that will be offered at the sale on Dec. 11: 
A one-sheet for Robert Wiene's 1921 "The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari" 
($25,000-$30,000), a 9x20-foot banner for "The Jazz Singer" from 1927 
($15,000-$20,000) and a half-sheet for "The Wizard of Oz" ($10,000-$15,000). 
CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
