<P>
GM PLANNING 10 SATURN MODELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
General Motors Corp.'s Saturn subsidiary is planning to produce 10 models by 
1994 and possibly expand its current one-plant operation, a trade journal said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
Saturn Corp. sent three car models -- single- and twin-cam sedans and a sporty 
coupe model -- to showrooms Oct. 12. 
</P>
<P>
The Automotive News reported in today's editions that the company will add a 
luxury sedan and coupe, a coupe convertible, two station wagons and two 
two-door hatchbacks. At least two of those vehicles will be added in each of 
the next three model years, the publication said. 
</P>
<P>
Saturn's $2-billion Spring Hill, Tenn., plant can produce up to 240,000 
vehicles annually. Automotive News said production there is scheduled to reach 
303,000 by the 1993 model year and 360,000 the following model year. 
</P>
<P>
That will probably force Saturn to build a second plant or expand the existing 
facility, it said. 
</P>
